[6] Cholera - India (Mumbai)
Date: Mon 16 Jul 2018 23:53 IST
Source: Times of India, Times News Network (TNN) [edited] [edited]
https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/2-from-dongri-byculla-treated-for-cholera/articleshow/65014677.cms


Cholera, an acute diarrheal infection that can kill if left untreated, has come back with July's [2018] heavy downpour. On [Mon 16 Jul 2018], the BMC [Municipal Corporation of Greater Mumbai] said that 2 residents had cholera from the B and E wards that cover areas such as Dongri, Byculla, and Mazgaon, have reported sporadic cases of cholera in the past as well.

BMC's executive health officer Dr Padmaja Keskar said that both patients were admitted to a municipal hospital and successfully treated. "Following the detection of these cases, we screened the areas but didn't find any more cases," she said.

Keskar said that mild cases of cholera are seen during monsoon. Last July 2017, too, a single case of cholera was reported.

